SIMPLE: scum
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scum
<hw>Scum</hw> <pr>(sk⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of Scand. origin;
cf. Dan. & Sw. <ets>skum</ets>, Icel. <ets>sk⟦umac⟧m</ets>, LG.
<ets>schum</ets>, D. <ets>schuim</ets>, OHG. <ets>sc⟦umac⟧m</ets>, G.
<ets>schaum</ets>; probably from a root meaning, to cover. ⟦root⟧158.
Cf. <er>Hide</er> skin, <er>Meerschaum</er>, <er>Skim</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>, <er>Sky</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The extraneous matter or impurities which rise to
the surface of liquids in boiling or fermentation, or which form on the
surface by other means; also, the scoria of metals in a molten state;
dross.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some to remove the <qex>scum</qex> as it did rise.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>refuse; recrement; anything vile or
worthless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great and innocent are insulted by the <qex>scum</qex> and
refuse of the people.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scum
<hw>Scum</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scummed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scumming</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take
the scum from; to clear off the impure matter from the surface of; to
skim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You that <qex>scum</qex> the molten lead.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden &
Lee.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sweep or range over the surface of.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wandering up and down without certain seat, they lived by
<qex>scumming</qex> those seas and shores as pirates.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scum
<hw>Scum</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To form a scum; to become covered
with scum. Also used figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Life, and the interest of life, have stagnated and
<qex>scummed</qex> over.</q> <rj><qau>A. K. H. Boyd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scumber</ent>⟦br⟧
